Name: Description
Poverty by Poverty Level:
Poverty level is the ratio of household income to the Federal Poverty Level (FPL). The FPL varies based on the number of children and adults in a household and the age of the head of household. In 2018, the annual income thresholds for a family of four would correspond to the following breakdown of poverty levels:
Below 100% FPL = Below $25,100 
100 to 199% FPL = $25,100 to $50,199
Below 200% FPL = Below $50,200
200 to 399% FPL = $50,200 to $100,399
400% FPL and above = $100,400 and above

Name: Source Notes
Poverty by Poverty Level: CCC Analysis of U.S. Census Bureau, American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates, Public Use Microdata Sample Files (2005-2018). Retrieved from https://data.census.gov/.

Name: Notes
Poverty by Poverty Level: The Census Bureau excludes institutionalized individuals, individuals living in military group quarters or college dorms, and unrelated individuals under 15 years of age from poverty estimates. Percents refer to the percent of the total population for whom poverty status was determined.
